---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import TracePlayer from "../../islands/TracePlayer.svelte";
import buggy from "../../../derived/search/buggy.trace.json";
import procedural from "../../../derived/search/procedural.trace.json";

// Buggy first: watch it record the value, then watch the correct version record the index.
const registers = [buggy, procedural];
---

<Base
  title="Linear search — GlassBox"
  description="Walk a list and find where a value lives — and watch the index-vs-value confusion that returns the wrong thing."
>
  <h1>Linear search</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    To find something in an unsorted list, you check each element in turn until you spot it. The subtle
    part is <em>what you report</em>: a search returns <strong>where</strong> the value is — its index —
    not the value itself, which you already knew. Step through and watch <code>found</code>.
  </p>

  <TracePlayer registers={registers} client:visible />

  <section class="explain card">
    <h2>What you are looking at</h2>
    <p>
      The list is <code>[4, 8, 15, 16, 23]</code> and we are looking for <code>15</code>. The right answer
      is its index, <code>2</code>. <code>found</code> starts at <code>-1</code>, a sentinel that means
      "not found yet" — no real index is negative, so it can never be mistaken for an answer.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Buggy</strong> — <code>found = nums[i]</code> stores the value that matched, so it ends at <code>15</code>: the thing we searched for, not where it lives. Useless as a position.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Procedural</strong> — <code>found = i</code> records the index, so it ends at <code>2</code>. One character apart, and only the state pane makes the difference undeniable.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="fineprint">
      Every state you see came from running the program under CPython's tracer at build time — see <a href="../../verification/">how GlassBox stays honest</a>.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .explain { margin-top: 1.4rem; }
  .explain ul { margin: 0.6rem 0; padding-left: 1.1rem; }
  .explain li { margin: 0.5rem 0; }
  .fineprint { color: var(--ink-faint); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 0; }
</style>
